status_message: The Roberts era begins on the Supreme Court: New Supreme Court Justice John Roberts, left, and then-Associate Justice John Paul Stevens pose for photographs in front of the court after Roberts' investiture ceremony. (Photo by H. Darr Beiser, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Hurricane Katrina makes landfall in Louisiana. The levee system in New Orleans failed, leading to severe flooding, seen here seven days after the hurricane devastated the city. (Photo by Michael Madrid, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Lance Armstrong wins his seventh straight Tour de France, the longest streak in the history of the Tour. Armstrong was 25 years old and one of the best cyclists in the world when he was diagnosed with testicular cancer in 1996, and his recovery and Tour triumphs made him a source of inspiration. He told USA TODAY in 2002, "It's not a burden, and I'll do it until they ask me not to." (Photo by Dan MacMedan, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Tens of thousands of people fill St. Peter's Square in Vatican City to mourn the passing of Pope John Paul II. His papacy lasted 26 years before he died at age 84.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: An undersea earthquake triggers a massive tsunami that kills more than 230,000 people in several Asian countries. Here, villagers in Krueng Raya, Indonesia, salvage building materials to carry into the hills to use to construct shelters in refugee camps away from the ocean. (Photo by Jack Gruber, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Death of the Curse: The Boston Red Sox celebrate after sweeping the St. Louis Cardinals in the 2004 World Series. Boston overcame a 3-games-to-0 deficit to the Yankees in the AL Championship Series en route to their first World Series title in 86 years. (Photo by Eileen Blass, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: American swimmer Michael Phelps dominates the headlines during the 2004 Olympic Games in Athens, Greece. He would win eight medals, including six gold. (Photo by Rob Schumacher, The Arizona Republic)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Harvard student Mark Zuckerberg launches www.thefacebook.com, a site for students at the school to connect online. It would be rolled out to more college campuses that year and eventually become the world's No. 1 social network, with more than 850 million users.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein is captured by U.S. forces when he is found hiding in a hole near Tikrit, Iraq. He was later executed in 2006.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Singer-songwriter Johnny Cash, regarded as one of the most influential of all time, dies at age 71.
link_name: Essential Johnny Cash

status_message: Before there were Angry Birds, the rise of the Internet made online gaming big business. This graphic from 2003 shows which portals were the most popular.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: A soldier on the upper floor of the Saddam Hussein Presidential Palace waves the victory sign to other infantry who work to secure the perimeter. The war in Iraq that began in 2003 would continue until 2011. (Photo by Jack Gruber, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Debris from the Space Shuttle Columbia spreads across Texas. Here, Leisa Pate talks to her daughters Destiny, left, and Aryan about a piece of the shuttle that landed in her brother's yard in Chinquapin Community, Texas. When the shuttle exploded upon entering the Earth's atmosphere, all seven crew members were killed. (Photo by H. Darr Beiser, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Texan Kelly Clarkson wins season one of "American Idol." "Idol" would go on to become one of the decade's most popular shows. It was just one of many reality shows with massive ratings in the early 2000s, which saw the birth of "Survivor," "The Apprentice," and "The Bachelorette." (Photo by Robert Hanashiro, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Halle Berry accepts the best actress Academy Award for her role in "Monster's Ball." She became the first African-American to win that award. (Photo by Robert Hanashiro, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: American figure skater Sarah Hughes reacts after finishing her long program at the 2002 Olympic Games in Salt Lake City. Hughes was in fourth place going into her final skate and took home the gold medal. "I really had nothing to lose," she told USA TODAY. "I thought there was no way in the world I could win." (Photo by Eileen Blass, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: In the cover story on Sept. 12, 2001, reporter Rick Hampson writes: "People ran through the ash-covered streets of Lower Manhattan like extras in a nuclear winter fantasy, chased by a mighty cloud of dust and debris from the office towers they once occupied. Others, some on fire, jumped from 30, 40, 80 stories. One couple held hands as they leapt."
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Smoke rises from the Pentagon on Sept. 11, 2011, after American Airlines Flight 77 is hijacked and flown into the U.S. military headquarters. This photo was taken from the USA TODAY headquarters, then in Arlington, Va. (Photo by Jym Wilson, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: New York City firefighters raise a flag at the site of the World Trade Center on Sept. 11, 2001. More than 2,700 people died at the site of the Twin Towers. (Photo by Ricky Flores, The Journal News)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: One of NASCAR's most prominent stars, Dale Earnhardt dies in a crash on the last lap of the Daytona 500. (Web Bryant, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: President George W. Bush takes the oath of office. Here, he shakes the hand of Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist. Bush's daughter Jenna is at center, and daughter Barbara is at right. (Photo by Tim Dillon, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: A front-page graphic published days after the 2000 election  shows why the race was still up in the air. With 37 electoral votes still undecided, both candidates lacked enough to win the election.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The front page of USA TODAY went through several changes late into the night on Nov. 7, 2000. The nation went to bed that night not knowing who would be the next president of the United States -- George W. Bush or Al Gore -- after Florida's tallies were unclear. It would be a battle over votes that would eventually go to the U.S. Supreme Court. The other big news of the night, Hillary Clinton's Senate win in New York, was eventually moved to the side.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: American Rulon Gardner defeats Russian Alexandre Kareline in the gold-medal Greco-Roman wrestling match at the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia. Kareline had not been beaten in 13 years. (Photo by Daryl Stone, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: USA TODAY marks the beginning of a new millennium with a 100-page special edition. The Y2K mishaps that some had predicted are largely averted.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: American tennis star Serena Williams wins her first singles major title at the U.S. Open. She and her older sister Venus would go on to dominate the women's tennis game for the next several years, overpowering with fast serves and physical strength that changed the game. (Photo by Robert Deutsch, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Much of the hype leading up to 2000 was around concerns that massive computer glitches would cause disruptions as the machines interpreted 2000 as 1900. Karen Mullenhour, of Wapakoneta, Ohio, shown here in 1999, told USA TODAY that she was not concerned. "Surely, everybody has records on paper of some kind," she said. "I don't see the problem." A USA TODAY/National Science Foundation poll in 1999 found that 3% of Americans still expected disasters of the magnitude that could cause the loss of life. (Photo by Terry Gilliam, AP for USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: John F. Kennedy Jr. is killed when the plane he is piloting crashed into the Atlantic Ocean near Martha's Vineyard. Also in the plane were his wife, Carolyn, and sister-in-law Lauren Bessette. The son of President John F. Kennedy, JFK Jr. was considered a prince of sorts for Americans.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Dozens of tornadoes break out over a four days across much of South, with the most damage near Oklahoma City. Here, Whitney Isbell, then 12, sits on the family car near their destroyed home. (Photo by Robert Deutsch, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold kill 12 students and one teacher in a shooting rampage at Columbine High School in Colorado. Images of students escaping through windows at the Littleton, Colo., school were broadcast on news networks. There was much confusion shortly after the massacre about how many people were killed.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: An exuberant Roberto Benigni accepts the Academy Award for best foreign language film, climbing over the backs of chairs to reach the stage.
link_name: Roberto Benigni goes wild at the Oscars®

status_message: Pop music dominated the airwaves in the late 1990s, with acts like Britney Spears, Backstreet Boys, and 'N Sync. In January 1999, Spears first became a household name.

Mark McGwire hits his 62nd home run to break the single-season record. Reporter Tom Weir writes: "With only a few feet to spare, McGwire's 62nd home run of 1998 nudged Roger Maris out of the record book and carved a new spot in baseball history for the goateed redhead whose drives typically have followed the same trajectory as St. Louis' sky-kissing Gateway Arch." McGwire would go on to hit 70 home runs that season. More than 10 years later, he would admit to having taken steroids through his career.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The first Harry Potter book by J.K. Rowling, "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone," hits stores in the U.S. The series would go on to see mammoth success and be turned into a movie franchise and theme park.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The Clintons -- Hillary, Chelsea, Bill, and dog Buddy -- depart from the South Lawn of the White House. It was their first public appearance since the president admitted to having a relationship with White House intern Monica Lewinsky. USA TODAY would later call for Clinton's resignation in an editorial. (Photo by Tim Dillon, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Apple CEO Steve Jobs launches the first iMac, which innovated with its all-in-one design and its use of a CD drive instead of a floppy drive. It was also the first Apple product to carry the "i" prefix.
link_name: The First iMac Introduction

status_message: The movie "Titanic" is released. It found mammoth commercial success and won 11 Academy Awards the following year.
link_name: Titanic - Official Trailer [1997]

status_message: Country crossover star Shania Twain releases "Come on Over," her second studio album. It would go on to sell more than 40 million copies and become the best-selling country album of all time.
This edition, published the day before Princess Diana's funeral, was long the best-selling USA TODAY newspaper. More than 3.2 million copies of this paper were sold.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Ellen DeGeneres makes headlines by revealing that she is gay. The character she portrayed on her hit TV show "Ellen" also came out, becoming TV's first gay lead character, provoking cheers from some and outrage from others. Here, DeGeneres presents an award at the 1996 Emmy Awards. (Photo by Robert Hanashiro, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: U.S. gymnastics coach Bela Karolyi carried an injured Kerri Strug just before she received her gold medal in the team competition at the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta. Strug competed in the vault despite a sprained ankle. This was the first Olympics shot using digital cameras by USA TODAY photographers. (Photo by Brian Porco, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The winner of the 1996 USA TODAY Ad Meter during the Super Bowl is a Pepsi commercial that shows a Coke delivery man trying to snag a Pepsi.
link_name: Pepsi Ad from 1996 - Coke Guy Caught on Cam (Your Cheatin' Heart)

status_message: Pixar releases its first feature film, "Toy Story," which would be the first of many animated films made completely by computer animation.
link_name: Toy Story Trailer

status_message: O.J. Simpson is acquitted of double murder charges. The verdict, shown live on television, divides the nation and is one of the most-watched events in television history. A USA TODAY/CNN Gallup poll, published here on the next day's front page, found that 73% of Americans said the former football star would have been found guilty if he were not rich. Simpson would later be held liable in a civil trial in the deaths of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald Goldman.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: 168 people are killed in a terrorist attack on the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City. The attack would remain the worst act of terrorism on U.S. soil until Sept. 11, 2011. "Car bombs are expected in Beirut or Belfast -- or maybe even in New York," read the cover story by reporter Sam Vincent Meddis. "But on a bright Midwest morning in downtown Oklahoma City, terrorism crossed a terrible threshold."
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Kurt Cobain, Nirvana frontman, commits suicide. Cobain's band defined a generation of music with its Seattle grunge roots.
link_name: Nevermind (Remastered)

status_message: At just 11, Anna Paquin wins a best supporting actress Academy Award for her performance in "The Piano."
link_name: Anna Paquin winning Best Supporting Actress for "The Piano"

status_message: Figure skater Nancy Kerrigan is clubbed on the leg at a Detroit ice rink. Her competitor Tanya Harding would later plead guilty to conspiracy charges and be banned from the sport. Kerrigan is shown here in a photo from 2000. (Photo by Eileen Blass, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: "Martha Stewart Living," a nationally syndicated television show featuring the lifestyle guru, premieres. Stewart would go on to oversee a media and merchandising empire. (Photo by Eileen Blass, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: President Bill Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton walk down Pennsylvania Avenue in Washington, D.C., on the day of Clinton's inauguration as the 42nd president of the United States. (Photo by H. Darr Beiser, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: "The Bodyguard" soundtrack is released, which would win that year's Grammy for album of the year and sell more than 40 million copies, becoming one of the best-selling albums of all time.
link_name: The Bodyguard - Original Soundtrack Album

status_message: American basketball players Michael Jordan, Clyde Drexler and Karl Malone accept the gold medal at the 1992 Olympic Games in Barcelona. It was the first Olympics in which professional basketball players were allowed to play. (Photo by Frank Becerra, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The U.S. National Guard patrols the streets of Los Angeles during the riots of 1992. The riots came after the acquittal of four Los Angeles police officers in the videotaped beating of Rodney King. (Photo by Robert Hanashiro, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The winner of 1992's USA TODAY Ad Meter during the Super Bowl is a Nike commercial featuring Michael Jordan and Bugs Bunny.
link_name: 1992 - Nike - Michael Jordan & Bugs Bunny

status_message: Los Angeles Lakers star Earvin "Magic" Johnson abruptly announces his retirement from basketball and discloses that he is HIV positive. He would begin to change Americans' perception of the face of the disease. "Sometimes people are a little naive and they think it can't happen to them. Sometimes we think only gay people can get it. And here I am saying that it can happen to anybody. Even me, Magic Johnson." Johnson is pictured here during the 1991 NBA Finals. (Photo by Porter Binks, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Whitney Houston performs the "Star Spangled Banner" at Super Bowl XXV in Tampa, Fla. The Super Bowl was held during the height of the Persian Gulf War and the performance would become an iconic one for Houston.
link_name: "Star Spangled Banner" -- Whitney Houston

status_message: USA TODAY publishes its first and only full-distribution Saturday paper to provide expanded coverage of the Persian Gulf War.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Mariah Carey's self-titled debut album is released. The singer-songwriter would sell tens of millions of records in the 90s and beyond.

The Hubble Space Telescope is launched into orbit aboard the Space Shuttle Discovery. This image, published in 2002, shows the Cone Nebula, which resides 2,500 light-years away in the constellation Monoceros. (NASA photo)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Nelson Mandela is freed after 27 years of imprisonment in South Africa. He would later be elected president of the African nation.
link_name: Flashback to 1990: Nelson Mandela freed from prison

status_message: The first episode of "The Simpsons" airs on FOX. It would go on to become the longest-running scripted, prime-time television show on American television. It also spawned a movie in 2007. Show creator Matt Groening is shown here at the movie's premiere that year. (Photo by Alison Redlich/Burlington Free Press)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The lead story here carries the dateline "AT THE BERLIN WALL." The Berlin Wall had just fallen, and East Germans were free to travel anywhere. The story by reporter Juan J. Walte reads: "The joyous scene occurred at the world's monument to communism, symbol for 28 years of the Cold War and testament to 191 East Germans who've perished trying to crawl, climb or even fly over it."
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: A major earthquake strikes the San Francisco area, causing severe damage and the collapse of a portion of the Bay Bridge. The tremor happened during warm-ups for the 1989 World Series. (Photo by H. Darr Beiser, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: As tanks roll in near Beijing's Tiananmen square after weeks of pro-democracy protests, a man heads into the street to block them. When the tanks veered left, he moved left. When the tanks moved forward, he held his ground. Bystanders eventually pulled him away, ending a five-minute standoff captured by TV cameras. His identity is still unknown.
link_name: Tank Man -- Tiananmen Square

status_message: The Exxon Valdez oil tanker strikes an underwater reef and spills hundreds of thousands of crude oil off the coast of Alaska. It would become one of the most significant environmental disasters of our time. Even 10 years later, the effects were still being felt, as shown in this 1999 photo of Gail Evanoff, president of the village of Chenega Bay, handling oiled rocks. (Photo by Al Grillo, for USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: In USA TODAY's first Ad Meter poll, which tracks consumers' opinions about Super Bowl commercials every year, an American Express commercial featuring comedians Jon Lovitz and Dana Carvey takes the top spot.
link_name: 1989 American Express Commercial (Dana Carvey and Jon Lovitz)

status_message: American diver Greg Louganis competes at the 1988 Summer Olympics in Seoul, South Korea. Louganis won his second consecutive Olympic gold there. He would hit his head during his dive from the 3-meter platform in Seoul, which later became newsworthy when it was revealed that he was HIV positive. (Photo by H. Darr Beiser, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Rush Limbaugh first hits the national airwaves and sees rapid success. He led the charge of conservative radio hosts who quickly gained unprecedented power, beaming their voices -- and opinions -- into the daily lives of millions of Americans. (Photo by Tim Dillon, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: "Black Monday," as it later came to be known, wiped out a half-trillion dollars in stocks' market value. It took until January 1989 for the Dow Jones to return to a pre-crash average.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The soundtrack to "Dirty Dancing" is released. It would become one of the best-selling albums of all time.
link_name: Various Artists

status_message: The U.S. Senate confirms Alan Greenspan as the chairman of the Federal Reserve -- a post he would hold until 2006 -- after being nominated by Ronald Reagan. During his tenure, he would hold the reins of the U.S. economy, helping it to a 10-year expansion. Upon his retirement, he was lauded as perhaps the greatest central banker ever. In this photo, Greenspan testifies for a Senate committee in 1998. (Photo by H. Darr Beiser, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Lt. Col. Oliver North, the central figure in the Iran-Contra affair, prepares to testify before Congress. North was the architect of the scheme that sent arms to Iran in exchange for money and possibly the release of hostages. The money was then sent -- illegally -- to the contras in Nicaragua, a right-wing organization that was battling Nicaragua's leftist government. (Photo by Tim Dillon, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: A telegram from Gannett President and CEO John Curley to USA TODAY founder shares some good news: The newspaper made a profit six months ahead of schedule.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: "The Oprah Winfrey Show" makes its national premiere. It would last for 25 years, become the top-rated daytime talk show and make a mogul out of Winfrey.
link_name: 1986 - Commercial - The Oprah Winfrey Show Premiere

status_message: The Chernobyl nuclear power plant in Ukraine explodes, releasing unprecedented amounts of radioactivity. The fall-out was 200 times that of the bombs dropped on Hiroshima and Nagasaki in World War II. Here, barbed wire surrounds apartments in Pripyat that were abandoned following the meltdown. Once home to 45,000 people, Pripyat, a city adjacent to Chernobyl, was a virtual ghost town when this photo was taken in 1996. (Photo by Jym Wilson, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The Space Shuttle Challenger breaks apart just more than a minute after it lifted off. Killed were all seven crew members, including Christa McAuliffe, who was set to become the first teacher in space. The launch was watched by millions of Americans, including many schoolchildren, who had gathered to see McAuliffe enter space. The front-page graphic in USA TODAY the next day showed the timeline of when the shuttle exploded.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: After directing box-office hits "E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial" and "Raiders of the Lost Ark," Steven Spielberg helmed his first period drama with "The Color Purple." It would make stars out of Whoopi Goldberg -- her first film -- and Oprah Winfrey.
link_name: The Color Purple (1985)

status_message: "Back to the Future," starring Michael J. Fox, hits theaters.
link_name: Back To The Future trailer

status_message: A commercial for USA TODAY hits the airwaves, featuring the singing talents of Willard Scott, Diahann Carroll, Willie Mays and even Charles Schwab.
link_name: USA Today Commercial with celebrities

status_message: The charity single "We Are the World" is recorded in Hollywood to raise funds for a famine in Ethiopia. Singers on the track included Michael Jackson, Diana Ross, Lionel Richie, Tina Turner and Bruce Springsteen.
link_name: USA for Africa - We are the World

status_message: American gymnast Mary Lou Retton earns perfect 10s on the floor exercise and vault to win the all-around title at the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles. Retton was the first American to win that title. (Photo by H. Darr Beiser, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The first Olympic Games covered by USA TODAY were the 1984 summer games in Los Angeles.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Geraldine Ferraro makes history as the first woman on a major party's presidential ticket. Democrat Walter Mondale chose her to be his running mate in 1984. (Photo by Barbara Ries, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Bruce Springsteen releases "Born in the U.S.A." -- his best-selling album that would include several hit singles.
link_name: Born In The U.S.A.

status_message: Aired during Super Bowl XVIII, the "1984" commercial that introduced the Macintosh would soon be regarded as one of the best commercials ever made.
link_name: 1984 Apple's Macintosh Commercial

status_message: President Ronald Reagan signs legislation to create a national holiday to honor the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.; the holiday is celebrated the third Monday in January. King would later be honored in 2011 with a memorial in Washington, D.C., shown in this photo in 2012. (Photo by H. Darr Beiser, USA TODAY)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Vanessa Williams wins the Miss America crown, the first African American to do so. She would later give back the title after nude photos surfaced and go on to become a successful recording artist and actress.
link_name: Miss America 1984 Crowning Moment

status_message: Madonna releases her first album.
link_name: Madonna

status_message: A foundation is established to create a Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum. Several cities were considered for the museum, including Detroit, Memphis and New York City. A poll of USA TODAY readers picked Cleveland, where it was opened in 1995. The museum is pictured here. (Photo by Ryan Haidet/WKYC)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The finale of "M*A*S*H" airs on CBS. At the time, it was the most-watched television program in America.
link_name: "M*A*S*H" finale promo

status_message: Michael Jackson releases "Thriller." It would become the best-selling album of all time.
This video from the Society for News Design takes a look back at how the launch of USA TODAY changed newspaper design.
link_name: #1: USA Today

status_message: The front page of the first edition of USA TODAY. The choice of the lead story -- the death of Princess Grace of Monaco -- was a controversial pick at the time. The move instantly set USA TODAY apart from other newspapers as a news source that would more directly reflect the interests of its readers.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The first issue of USA TODAY is celebrated on the National Mall in Washington in an event featuring President Ronald Reagan, speaking; Senate Majority Leader Howard H. Baker, Jr., left; Speaker of the House Thomas P. "Tip" O'Neill; USA TODAY founder Al Neuharth; and first lady Nancy Reagan.
link_name: Timeline Photos
